olive oil
1 tomato
2 radish
1 bag salad leaves
1 bag herbs
½ lemon
1 packet beef mince
1 egg
1 packet fine breadcrumbs
1 packet Greek salad cheese/feta cheese
20 g butter
1 sachet vegetable stock powder
1 packet couscous
3 clove garlic
1 packet Greek-Style Yoghurt
1 sachet Middle Eastern spice blend
¾ cup water

Finely chop garlic and tomato. Roughly chop
radish, salad leaves and herbs. Zest lemon to get
a pinch, then slice into wedges.

In a large bowl, combine beef mince, Middle Eastern seasoning, the egg, fine breadcrumbs and 1/2 the garlic. Crumble in cheese and mix well. Season with pepper. Using damp hands, shape heaped spoonfuls of beef mixture into meatballs, then transfer to a plate. You should get 4-5 meatballs per person.

In a large frying pan, heat a drizzle of olive oil over medium-high heat. Cook meatballs, turning, until browned and cooked through, 8-10 minutes.

Meanwhile, melt the butter in a medium saucepan over medium-high heat. Cook remaining garlic until fragrant, 1 minute. Add the water and vegetable stock powder and bring to the boil. Add couscous and a drizzle of olive oil. Stir to combine, cover with a lid and remove from heat. Set aside until the water is absorbed, 5 minutes. Fluff up with a fork.

When the couscous is done, combine tomato,
radish, salad leaves, herbs, couscous, lemon
zest and a squeeze of lemon juice in a medium
bowl. Season to taste. In a small bowl, combine
Greek-style yoghurt and a good squeeze of lemon
juice. Season to taste.

TIP: Make the couscous tabbouleh in the saucepan
and save on washing up!

Divide couscous tabbouleh between bowls, then top with Middle Eastern beef and crumbly cheese meatballs. Drizzle with lemon yoghurt dressing. Serve with any remaining lemon wedges.